Consider the following C program segment:
char p[20];
int i;
char *s = "string";
int length = strlen(s);
for (i = 0; i < length; i++)
    p[i] = s[length - i];
printf("%s", p);
The output of the program is:
A. gnirts
B. string
C. gnirt
D. no output is printed

Consider the following C program:
double foo (double);  /* Line 1 */
int main()
{
    double da, db;
    // input da
    db = foo(da);
}
double foo(double a)
{
    return a;
}
The above code compiled without any error or warning. If Line 1 is deleted, the above code will show:
A. no compile error or warning
B. some compiler warnings not leading to unintended results
C. some compiler warnings due to type mismatch potentially leading to unintended results
D. compiler errors
